<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[113,772,725,1998]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
REMARKS ON KARYOTYPES (
<figureCitation box="[429,596,725,749]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Figs. 195–209</figureCitation>
). We analyzed male karyotypes of four 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[414,490,757,781]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[414,490,757,781]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species from the Horn of Africa (
<tableCitation box="[234,323,789,813]" captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="32.[115,171,447,468]" captionTargetId="graphics-722@32.[113,1474,244,422]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Table 3. The diploid numbers, the postpachytene configuration (Ppt configuration), the percentage of the total chromosome length of the diploid set (% TCL) and the localities of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5AE76644DC7D403B6862FE42FCF25192" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" tableUuid="5AE76644DC7D403B6862FE42FCF25192">Table 3</tableCitation>
). The cytogenetic characteristics of all species correspond to the typical features of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. L. Koch" authorityYear="1837" box="[113,212,853,877]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Buthidae</taxonomicName>
such as holocentric organization, achiasmatic meiosis in males, and lower number of chromosomes (e. g. 
<bibRefCitation author="MATTOS, V. F." box="[143,360,917,941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="121 - 136" refId="ref10304" refString="MATTOS, V. F., D. M. CELLA, L. S. CARVALHO, D. M. CANDIDO &amp; M. C. SCHNEIDER. 2013. High chromosome variability and the presence of multivalent associations in buthid scorpions. Chromosome Research, 21: 121 - 136." type="journal article" year="2013">Mattos et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). All examined specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2011" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="awashensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus awashensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kovařík &amp; Šťáhlavský &amp; Elmi, 2020" authorityName="Kovařík &amp; Šťáhlavský &amp; Elmi" authorityYear="2020" box="[261,384,949,973]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pococki" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[261,384,949,973]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">B. pococki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[399,469,949,973]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[399,425,949,973]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">sp</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[447,462,949,973]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1900" box="[537,673,949,973]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zeylensis">
<emphasis box="[537,673,949,973]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">B. zeylensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possess 2n=22 (
<figureCitation box="[202,544,981,1005]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Figs. 195, 201, 204, 205, 208</figureCitation>
). We found only 21 chromosomes in karyotype of analysed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1900" box="[559,771,1013,1037]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berberensis">
<emphasis box="[559,771,1013,1037]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus berberensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[122,219,1045,1069]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 198</figureCitation>
). The reduction of the diploid number is probably consequence of heterozygous fusion of chromosomes. This 
<typeStatus box="[113,160,1110,1134]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">type</typeStatus>
of chromosomal rearrangement forms conspicuous trivalent during postpachytene (
<figureCitation box="[465,562,1141,1165]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 199</figureCitation>
). Moreover, fusion of two chromosomes form one extra large chromosome in the karyotype of this species (
<figureCitation box="[487,588,1205,1229]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 200</figureCitation>
). Except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2011" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="awashensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus awashensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the karyotypes of the all analysed species are typical with one pair of chromosomes with distinctive length whereas the subsequent chromosomes are shorter and gradually decrease in length (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Figs. 200, 203, 206, 209</figureCitation>
). Similar one longer pair of chromosomes is known also in karyotypes of all karyotyped 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1828" box="[541,681,1397,1421]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Androctonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[541,681,1397,1421]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Androctonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="SADILEK" box="[121,355,1429,1456]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="69 - 76" refId="ref10433" refString="SADILEK, D., P. NGUYEN, H. KOC, F. KOVARIK, E. A. YAGMUR &amp; F. STAHLAVSKY. 2015. Molecular cytogenetics of Androctonus scorpions: an oasis of calm in the turbulent karyotype evolution of the diverse family Buthidae. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 115: 69 - 76." type="journal article" year="2015">SadÍlek et al., 2015</bibRefCitation>
). This similarity of karyotypes may reflect phylogenetic relationships that was already proposed in previous phylogenetic analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="FET" box="[522,712,1493,1517]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref9714" refString="FET, V., B. GANTENBEIN, A. V. GROMOV, G. LOWE &amp; W. R. LOURENCO. 2003. The first molecular phylogeny of Buthidae (Scorpiones). Euscorpius, 4: 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="2003">Fet et al., 2003</bibRefCitation>
). We observed multivalent association (ten chromosomes of different length) in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2011" box="[323,530,1557,1581]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="awashensis">
<emphasis box="[323,530,1557,1581]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus awashensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
during postpachytene (
<figureCitation box="[122,283,1589,1613]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Figs. 196–197</figureCitation>
). This chain of chromosomes is consequence of multiple reciprocal translocations. Although this 
<typeStatus box="[693,740,1622,1646]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">type</typeStatus>
of chromosome rearrangement does not affect chromosome numbers, it may however considerably change the size of the chromosomes (e. g. 
<bibRefCitation author="KOVARIK" box="[378,605,1717,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref9978" refString="KOVARIK, F., G. LOWE, M. SEITER, J. PLISKOVA &amp; F. STAHLAVSKY. 2015. Scorpions of Ethiopia (Arachnida: Scorpiones). Part II. Genus Babycurus Karsch, 1886 (Buthidae), with description of two new species. Euscorpius, 196: 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="2015">KovařÍk et al., 2015</bibRefCitation>
). It is probably the reason why this species has not one extra large pair of chromosomes, the typical feature of the remaining species with only bivalents (
<figureCitation box="[353,584,1813,1837]" captionStart="Figures 195–209" captionStartId="30.[113,190,1852,1874]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,234,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-20@30.[159,1436,234,1839]" captionText="Figures 195–209: Male mitotic metaphases (195, 198, 201, 204, 207), postpachytenes (196, 199, 202, 205, 208) and ideograms (197, 200, 203, 206, 206) (y axis - % of the diploid chromosome length, dark grey marks chromosomes in multivalent association) of Buthus species from the Horn of Africa. Figures 195–197. B. awashensis, topotype from locality 12EX (2n=22, 6II+CX), Figures 198–200. B. berberensis from locality 19SO (2n=21, 9II+CIII), Figures 201–203. B. pococki sp. n., paratopotype (2n=22, 11II), Figures 204–206. B. pococki sp. n., paratype from locality 19SN (2n=22, 11II), Figures 207–209. B. zeylensis from locality 19SH (2n=22, 11II). Arrows show chromosomes in multivalent association during postpachytene. Asterisks show extra-large chromosome from multivalents. Arrowheads indicate large chromosome pair. Scale bar: 10 μm (195–196, 198–199, 201–202, 204–205, 207–208)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4770195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4770195/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Figs. 202, 205, 208</figureCitation>
). Despite of the mentioned small differences among analysed species, the karyotypes of species from the Horn of Africa fully correspond to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Amoreux" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[408,608,1909,1933]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occitanus">
<emphasis box="[408,608,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus occitanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[696,771,1910,1933]" name="France" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">France</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="GUENIN" box="[121,287,1941,1965]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="89 - 96" refId="ref9832" refString="GUENIN, H. A. 1961. Contribution a la connaissance cytologique des scorpions: les chromosomes de Buthus occitanus Amor. (I). Vie et Milieu, 12: 89 - 96." type="journal article" year="1961">Guénin, 1961</bibRefCitation>
), and the karyotypes seem to be very conservative within the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[451,527,1973,1997]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[451,527,1973,1997]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Buthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
